pgTitle: List of Ottoman governors of Egypt

rows.text: Rebelled, declared himself sultan; was executed
Remained for 3 months, organized the civil and military system of Ottoman Egypt
Served only a few months as acting governor
Also known as Sufi Ali Pasha or Hadım Ali Pasha
Also known as Sufi or Sofu Ali Pasha
Of a mild disposition, but thieves multiplied during his short term
Put to death many thieves, stunting robbery in the region for centuries
Dismissed after being unable to collect enough taxes
Attempted to get the mutiny under control, but failed
Left governance mostly in the hands of his family, corruption ensued
Educated in various sciences and formerly governor of Yemen
Drought led to his dismissal and successor accused him of financial fraud
Soldiers, angry at the rapid change in governors, restored him
Invested and speculated heavily in local merchants and businesses
Only appeared 6 times in public, but was well-liked
Army forced his resignation after his brutality and murder of a local bey
Known for his "gentle, impartial, and prosperous administration"
Dismissed and executed either for his cruelty
Cruel and violent, but kept the army in check
Confiscated many emirs' and wealthy residents' inheritances
His officials were the de jure rulers and plundered the land
All of his rule was reportedly "only a series of confusions and revolutions"
Neglected affairs and was soon dismissed, but no insurrections occurred
His rule was "agitated by great disturbances," and he amassed great wealth
After his dismissal, he was jailed by successor for not paying debts
Known locally as Abu'l-Nur, "father of light", for restoring buildings
Known locally as Gazi for putting down a rebellion; jailed afterwards
Some soldiers tried to replace him with his predecessor but failed
Jailed by the army due to his violence during tax collection
Also called by the epithet Kethüda/Ketkhoda, but mostly just Hasan Pasha
Acting governor, installed by soldiers; served for 5 to 8 months
Also known by the epithets Boşnak (Bosniak), Sarı, Dizveren, and Muradi
Jailed and exiled by the sultan after dismissal
There was an insurrection begun by a Turkish religious fanatic, but it failed
Held the office for a minuscule amount of time
Ended the remains of the insurrection begun in 1711 by the religious fanatic
Deposed by the forces of Çerkes Mehmed Bey after displeasing him
His rule was peaceful and free of insurrections
Troops rioted, demanding pay and rations from the granary
He was a "profound scholar"; forced to step down by local troops
Died very soon after taking office
Deposed in August 1761 by the local emirs
Died soon after taking office in September 1764
Became acting governor after forcing out the last governor
He was replaced by the sultan in late September 1779 with Ibrahim Pasha
He died in office in November 1779 (one month after his arrival)
His rule was peaceful and he was well-liked by the emirs
His identity is unknown, perhaps partially named "Sharif/Şerif Pasha"
He deposed his predecessor, but he was already the de facto ruler of Egypt
The incoming governor made him acting governor on February 20, 1785
De facto ruler when Keki Abdi Pasha refused the office until emirs were defeated
Appointed on 24 October 1786, but left governance to Hasan Pasha for a while
Dismissed 21 September 1801, he left for his estate on 8 January 1802
Took power in June against the Albanians, although they had de facto control
Sent by the Ottomans in July to take back Egypt from the Albanians, but killed
